data.label: The Patient
data.description: "The Patient" is a notable entity in the knowledge graph, recognized as a winner of the Best Drama Series Golden Globe. It is a film set in pre-colonial sub-Saharan Africa, specifically in the Gambia, and is part of the TV miniseries "Root". The film is notable for holding the record for the most Primetime Emmy Awards won per ceremony. The film's score was composed by Gerald Fried. As a named individual, "The Patient" is part of a 1970s American television miniseries. The film explores the theme of American slavery and is based on American novels. It is known for containing scenes of corporal punishment. The works of Maya Angelou are associated with it. "The Patient" is a Peabody Award-winning television program and has been broadcast by the Nine Network and Sky One. It was filmed in Los Angeles and is based on an American novel. It is a Warner Bros. Discovery television program and is also part of Disney+ Hotstar original programming.

data.label: Anthony Redmon
data.description: Anthony Redmon is a named individual, born in 1971, who is recognized as an American football offensive guard and a player of American football from Alabama. data.description: "Fight the Power" is a song by the band Public Enemy. It was released as a single in 1989 and is recognized as a Motown single. The song is known for its political rap content and is specifically a song against racism and xenophobia. It is also considered an autobiography and a cultural depiction of John Wayne. The song was written by Chuck D, Eric "Vietnam" Sadler, Hank Shocklee, and Keith Shocklee, and was produced by the Bomb Squad. It was also written for films. The music video for "Fight the Power" was directed by Spike Lee. The song is also referred to as the "1989 song of the same name".

data.label: Milton Galamison
data.description: Milton Galamison is a notable figure in African-American history, known for his activism with the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP). He was born on March 25, 1923, and died in 1988. His birthplaces are listed as Pennsylvania, Long Island, New York City, Brooklyn, New York State, and New Jersey, indicating a strong connection to the East Coast, particularly New York. He resided in Brooklyn and was an active participant in New York City's activist scene. Galamison was also an alumnus of the Princeton Theological Seminary. He is alternatively known as "Galamison, Milton A." and his information is corroborated by DBpedia.

data.label: Van Loon's Lives
data.description:
